If I set a custom `query parser`, as explained in the [docs](http://expressjs.com/en/4x/api.html#app.set), the custom query parser only gets used if I define it immediately after the app is created (ie. before any middleware is added).  

This works:
```js
const app = express();
app.set('query parser', function(str) {
  return qs.parse(str, { arrayLimit: Infinity });
});
app.use(bodyParser.json())
app.use(Router())
```

This does not:
```js
const app = express();
app.use(bodyParser.json())
app.set('query parser', function(str) {
  return qs.parse(str, { arrayLimit: Infinity });
});
app.use(Router())
```

In both cases, the call to `app.set()` succeeds, and `app.settings` reflects the custom query parser that I provided.  

However, the custom query parser is never invoked in the second example, and express continues to use the default `"extended"` parser.  

---

Personally, I do not have any particular problem with this limitation, as it seems exceedingly unlikely that one would need to alter this setting at runtime.  

However, the documentation should probably indicate this caveat, and it may be beneficial for `app.set()` to throw an error when making configuration changes that are known to be ineffective or illegal.

